hange in vegetation types over time and determine the capacity of the land to carry stock.  Under the Pastoral Land Management and Conservation Act 1989 (Act), the assessment of the lands comprising a pastoral lease is required before the tenure of any lease is extended, and for any lease this assessment must be carried out at intervals not exceeding 14 years.  Photopoints were established on 218 Pastoral properties and about 5500 permanent photopoint sites were established.  At each photopoint site, information on plant composition and abundance, grazing or other impacts or disturbance, soil erosion and soil surface cover was collected, together with detail on location of the site, GPS coordinates, etc. as an aid to future re-visits.  At many of the sites the soil profile was also described, together with details of slope, geology etc.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>132.513476,-26.015116 141.000814,-26.015116 141.000814,-34.011204 132.513476,-34.011204 132.513476,-26.015116</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">136.757145,-30.01316</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/alis/ast</span><span class="read-more">Read more</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/management-and-study-of-arid-lands-lease-inspection-and-assessment-program" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin">3</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Biological Database of South Australia: Birds SA - Personal Bird Records</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px;">Birds SA  (South Australian Ornithology Association) bird records from members for the whole of South Australia (1900-2008). Records have not been published in South Australian Ornithology Association Journal 'Wingspan'.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>129.00211,-26.12861 143.07883,-26.12861 143.07883,-39.65 129.00211,-39.65 129.00211,-26.12861</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">136.04047,-32.889305</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/bdbsa/564</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/biological-database-of-south-australia-birds-sa-personal-bird-records" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin">4</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Biological Database of South Australia: Biological Survey of South Australia: Innamincka Regional Reserve Biological Survey</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px;">The main aim of this survey was to collect data on the vegetation communities within the south eastern section of the Innamincka Regional Reserve to enable the classification and mapping of the floristic composition and structure of the vegetation groups within the park.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>140.58898,-27.55983 140.99628,-27.55983 140.99628,-28.40109 140.58898,-28.40109 140.58898,-27.55983</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">140.79263,-27.98046</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/bdbsa/194</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/biological-database-of-south-australia-biological-survey-of-south-australia-innamincka-regional-reserve-biological-survey" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin">5</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Biological Database of South Australia: Biological Survey of South Australia: Stony Deserts</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px; overflow: hidden;">This study aims to provide an overview of the patterns of variation in distribution and abundance of the natural resources of the Stony Deserts (Lambina Pastoral Lease), identify crucial habitats and recommend conservation management. Survey is part of the Biological Survey of SA programme run by the Biological Survey &amp; Monitoring group in DEH. Survey areas defined in a DEH spatial layer managed by DEH Environmental Information Group. Survey was conducted in 1993.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>132.63593,-25.91084 141.98454,-25.91084 141.98454,-36.36598 132.63593,-36.36598 132.63593,-25.91084</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">137.310235,-31.13841</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/bdbsa/69</span><span class="read-more">Read more</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/biological-database-of-south-australia-biological-survey-of-south-australia-stony-deserts" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin">6</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Biological Database of South Australia: Biological Survey of South Australia: Sandy Desert</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px;">The Sandy desert survey is part of the Biological Survey of SA programme run by the Biological Survey &amp; Monitoring group in DEH. Generally standard methodology used. Survey areas defined in a DEH spatial layer managed by DEH Environmental Information Group.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>126.05622,-24.74009 143.87109,-24.74009 143.87109,-35.77717 126.05622,-35.77717 126.05622,-24.74009</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">134.963655,-30.25863</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/bdbsa/94</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/biological-database-of-south-australia-biological-survey-of-south-australia-sandy-desert" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin">7</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Management and Study of Arid Lands: Lease Inspection</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px;">The inspection process involves land condition monitoring in conjunction with assessing the impacts of the current grazing practices.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>133.053732,-26.013588 141.001611,-26.013588 141.001611,-34.112725 133.053732,-34.112725 133.053732,-26.013588</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">137.0276715,-30.0631565</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/alis/ins</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/management-and-study-of-arid-lands-lease-inspection" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin">8</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Biological Database of South Australia: Rare and Threatened Species Protection Strategies / Biological Database of South Australia: Biological Survey of South Australia: Rare Rodents Project</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px; overflow: hidden;">Distributional data for target and off-target species of small mammals collected as part of the Rare Rodent Project. The Rare Rodent project involves the ongoing monitoring of two species of threatened rodent, the Plains Rat (Pseudomys australis) and the Dusky Hopping Mouse (Notomys fuscus). The project aims to look at distribution, status and ecology of the species (in Outback South Australia). Currently there are two monitoring sites for each species, which are visited twice a year. The project began in 1992 and hopes to continue in the long term subject to funding. An additional species, the Kultarr (Antechinomys laniger), is now being targeted as part of the project due to its unknown status.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>133.50415,-23.92131 141.70679,-23.92131 141.70679,-83.6538 133.50415,-83.6538 133.50415,-23.92131</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">137.60547,-53.787555</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/bdbsa/48</span><span class="read-more">Read more</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/biological-database-of-south-australia-rare-and-threatened-species-protection-strategies-biological-database-of-south-australia-biological-survey-of-south-australia-rare-rodents-project" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin">9</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Biological Database of South Australia: SAOA Records from Newsletters (G Carpenter)</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px;">Records from South Australian Ornithological Association newsletters.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>129.00388,-26.00089 143.4537,-26.00089 143.4537,-40.50012 129.00388,-40.50012 129.00388,-26.00089</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">136.22879,-33.250505</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/bdbsa/306</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/biological-database-of-south-australia-saoa-records-from-newsletters-g-carpenter" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin2">10</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Biological Database of South Australia: South Australian Museum Non- Specimen Records</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px;">This project contains sighting records data where the specimen or photo (or maybe description) has been confirmed by the relevant Curator at the SAMuseum. Data is from 1932-2010, across the whole of South Australia.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>130.10269,-26.06915 141.63456,-26.06915 141.63456,-38.05082 130.10269,-38.05082 130.10269,-26.06915</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">135.868625,-32.059985</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/bdbsa/597</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/biological-database-of-south-australia-south-australian-museum-non-specimen-records" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin2">11</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Biological Database of South Australia: Bird Atlas Data 1996-2006 (Birds Australia)</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px;">Bird Atlas Data 1996-2006 (Birds Australia).</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>129,-25.99898 141.01666,-25.99898 141.01666,-38.93208 129,-38.93208 129,-25.99898</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">135.00833,-32.46553</span><br><span class="key hide">aekos.org.au/collection/sa.gov.au/bdbsa/213</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">07-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/biological-database-of-south-australia-bird-atlas-data-1996-2006-birds-australia" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin2">12</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Aspect (3" resolution) derived from 1" SRTM DEM-S</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px; overflow: hidden;">Aspect measures the direction in which a land surface slope faces. The direction is expressed in degrees from north.

The aspect product was derived from the Smoothed Digital Elevation Model (DEM-S; ANZCW0703014016), which was derived from the 1 second resolution SRTM data acquired by NASA in February 2000. The calculation of aspect from DEM-S accounted for the varying spacing between grid points in the geographic projection. 

This 3” resolution version of the aspect product has been masked by the 3” water and ocean mask datasets.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>113,-10 154,-10 154,-44 113,-44 113,-10</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">133.5,-27</span><br><span class="key hide">102.100.100/7681</span><span class="read-more">Read more</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">25-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/aspect-3-resolution-derived-from-1-srtm-dem-s" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin2">13</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Slope (3" resolution) derived from 1" SRTM DEM-S</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px; overflow: hidden;">Slope measures the inclination of the land surface from the horizontal. The percent slope and degrees slope products represent this inclination as the ratio of change in height to distance.

The slope (percentage) and slope (degrees) products were derived from the Smoothed Digital Elevation Model (DEM-S; ANZCW0703014016), which was derived from the 1 second resolution SRTM data acquired by NASA in February 2000. The calculation of slope from DEM-S accounted for the varying spacing between grid points in the geographic projection. 

The 3 second resolution slope products were generated from the 1 second percent slope/degrees slope products and masked by the 3” water and ocean mask datasets.</p> <ul class="spatial hide"><li>113,-10 154,-10 154,-44 113,-44 113,-10</li></ul><span class="spatial_center hide">133.5,-27</span><br><span class="key hide">102.100.100/7757</span><span class="read-more">Read more</span></div></td><td><p class="datePublished">25-09-2012</p><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="show"></a><div id="metabutton" class="expand" style="display: none;"><a target="_blank" href="http://portal-dev.tern.org.au/slope-3-resolution-derived-from-1-srtm-dem-s" class="greenGradient smallRoundedCorners viewmeta">View Metadata</a></div></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><a href="javascript:void(0);" class="pin2">14</a></td><td><h2><a href="javascript:void(0);">Topographic Position Index (3" resolution) derived from 1" SRTM DEM-S</a></h2><div id="metadesc" class="expand" style="display: none;"><p style="height: 48px; overflow: hidden;">Topographic Position Index (TPI) is a topographic position classification identifying upper, middle and lower parts of the landscape. This dataset includes a mask that identifies where topographic position cannot be reliably derived in low relief areas.

